These are designed to replace the gears inside a nerf Roughcut 2x4 if the original ones break.
The centre hole will need to be drilled out with a 3mm drill bit.

To replace them you first need to open the gun up (colours may be different depending on what version you own):
Unscrew the 3 screws in the priming handle first and remove it.
Next undo all the screws in the main body of the gun and open it up. (be careful of the small orange part and spring in the tactical rail at the top of the gun, it may fly off and get lost). You might want to take pictures at this point to help you put it back together. Inside you should see the two plunger tubes connected to the front barrel. The two plungers are connected to the main mechanism. This consists of a rack gear (flat gear) connected to the priming handle, two gears (one large and one small) and a second rack gear connected to the plungers. There is also the trigger, trigger catch and two other catches. These two catches have a habit of pinging out and getting lost, so make sure you get a good look at how they go back together. Remove the trigger, it should just pull out with a little twist. Next remove the plungers from the top rack gear. This is easiest done by gently twisting one of the plungers.
You should now be able to see the two catches clearer, there is one on each side of the mechanism. Undo the 3 screws holding the mechanism together. There is also a small clip at the bottom of the mechanism that should come off easily once the screws are removed.
It should now be easy to remove and replace the two gears, make sure you get them the right way around, small one at the top, large one at the bottom.
Make sure that the two catches didn't fly off and reattach the top half of the mechanism with the 3 screws. Make sure that both rack gears can travel the full length of the mechanism and that all the catches work.
Reconnect the plungers (make sure that the catch is being pressed down by the plunger, otherwise it wont prime) and the trigger.
It should now be simple to replace all the parts back into the outer shell and reattach all the screws. Attach the priming handle last.

Inspired by my visit to Comic Con 2013, this is one wicked calibration test.  Two halves of the cube will slide together to form Lemarchand's box; a fictional lock puzzle or puzzle box appearing in horror stories by Clive Barker, or in works based on his original stories.  
The various parts can be printed in different colors, or ommitted, for creating storage nooks.  The center pins can be used as ink wells, if you need to write something in blood.

ABS works fine.  Doesn;t warp (at least not for me).  Use 0.4mm layers, and any infill you like.  This creates double walls.  You can scale the whole thing down by half, and print single walled, but the fit may be even tighter.  
Print two copies of the main cube structure.  Slide them together in one of two configurations.  
Warning:  Do not attempt this print without a well calibrated machine, or you will encouter much pain and suffering.  
Even if you manage to print it perfectly, be aware that the box pieces fit very precisely, and the corrugation of the layers will make it impossible to separate the two, unless you take some precautions first.  I recommend flat filing the inner mating surfaces smooth, and testing the fit every half inch or so, until you can easily push the two main parts together, and bring them back apart.  
Oh, and if they do get stuck together, just be sure it's in the portal closed position, otherwise, who knows what might come through from the other side.

description.text:
A newer, actually printable version is here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1922547 I modified the script to support simple halftone dithering, so each pixel can have a gray value between 0 and 1, the brighter the pixel is, the bigger the hole created for it is. The picture has to be 75x75 pixels for customizer, if you want to use higher resolutions you have to download the scad file and use OpenSCAD to create it on your local machine. The image array can be created with this fiddle: http://jsfiddle.net/threonin/6dr8qu41/
It scales exponentially with resolution, so be careful, it can eat up lots of RAM very quickly.
If white_threshold is below 1 everything above it will be rendered as empty pixel, if you use it you have to make sure there are no dark patches surrounded by bright areas, as they would be free floating in the air then.
Everything below black_threshold will be solid black with no hole in it.
white_max and black_min can be used to limit the range of the hole sizes, so they don't become too small or the walls in between too big.
Cutoff is used to make the bottom flat for easier printing, set it to 100 if you don't want that.
You probably need to play around with these values to get something that is actually printable, I still don't have a printer so I don't know what is possible.
To preview the result you can use a similar setup as in the blendfile I uploaded. Edit: I noticed the images were much too dark, I fixed this now, the old version is in stereographic_flat_dither.scad.old

I wanted a part with a variety of nicely sized holes and pegs, so I made one.

Holes/pegs are 10mm, 8mm, 6mm, and 4mm diameters. Overall it is 45mm by 25 mm. The extra squareish area near the large peg is 15mm by 15mm. The holes are 5mm deep, and the pegs are 5mm high. I tried to make the dimensions as pleasant as possible so I wouldn't have to remember them exactly.

Diese Sammlung von Bauteilen ersetzt die übliche Z-Achsenkonstruktion des 3Drag / K8200 durch eine zentrale Z-Achse. Dies ist eine Modifikation von sgabolab. Ihr findet es unter:
http://sgabolab.blogspot.it/p/blog-page_16.html
Ich habe aber es dahingehend geändert, weil nicht alle Bauteile passend waren und auch nicht alle Bauteile verfügbar waren. Weiterhin besteht es aus einem Getriebe, welches eine Übersetzung von 1:4,3 liefert und somit die Präzision in der Z-Achse deutlich erhöht. Verwendet wird eine Trapezspindel TR8-1.5. Für das Komplettieren werden folgende Dinge benötigt:
  • Schrauben M4 mit passender Mutter
  • 3x Kugellager 608
  • 3x Spindelmutter 6-Kant (SW 17) für TR8-1.5 (ähnliche: http://www.metallbau-pietrzak.de/shop/product_info.php/products_id/5350)
  • 1x Spindel 500mm TR8-1.5
  • Ersatzzahnrad 10 Zähne für Extrudermotor (Original)
    • Nach dem Aufbau ist das Ändern der Steps pro mm notwendig. Eine grobe Annäherung kann super mit dem Werkzeug aus RepetierHost berechnen. Übersetzungsverhältnis 1:4.3 Weiterhin ist bei den Bauteilen ein Deckel enthalten, dieser wird bei meinem Gehäuse benötigt, da die Spindel nach oben aus dem Gehäuse wandert. Dieser Deckel ist aber nicht notwendig für die Z-Achsenmodifikation. Ich hoffe euch hilft diese Konstruktion weiter.
    Die Autodesk-Inventor-Dateien sind auch unter den Downloads zufinden. Bei mir hat sich das Druckbild verbessert und es gibt kein Verkanten mehr. Für Fragen stehe ich gerne zur Verfügung.

This collection of components replaced the usual Z-axis design of 3Drag / K8200 through a central Z axis. This is modification of sgabolab. You find the project on:
http://sgabolab.blogspot.it/p/blog-page_16.html
I modified it, because not all components are perfect or exist. Furthermore, it consists of a gear, which is a translation of 1: 4.3, and thus provides considerably increases the precision in the Z-axis. Used a trapezoidal spindle TR8-1.5. Of completing the following things are needed:
  • M4 screws with matching nut
  • 3x ball bearings 608
  • 3x spindle nut 6-Kant (SW 17) for TR8-1.5 (similar: http://www.metallbau-pietrzak.de/shop/product_info.php/products_id/5350)

However, this cover is not necessary for the Z-axis modification. I hope you will help this construction further.

title: Gadgets3D LCD mount for Prusa i3

description.text:
This is designed for i3 single sheet version, but could also be used with the box frame version. It bolts on the back side of the frame, where Z axis rod holders are. The design is compatible with my i2 LCD holder, so if you are upgrading from i2 to i3, there is no need to print the LCD part again. There is also a clippable version in the files that you can download, so you can choose whether to install the LCD on Z top screws or just clip it on the frame. Of course the screw installation will be a bit sturdier. BOM:
  • 7 x 20 mm M3 screw
  • 2 x 16 mm M3 screw
  • 7 x M3 nut
  • 5 x M3 washer

• Print out the parts. Print two hinge bits.
  • Use acetone (ABS) or glue (PLA) to attach the hinge bits to the main part. They should be placed in the back side slots.
  • Attach LCD panel to the X-shape holder.
  • Attach LCD holder to the main part using a bolt, nut and washer.
  • Attach the assembly to i3 frame, on the back side of Z axis top holders. You might have to change default Z holder bolts to longer 16 or 20 mm ones.
  • Connect LCD to RAMPS, upload software, and enjoy!

description.text:
This is an introductory project that is great for introducing teachers and students to 3D printing. It requires very little specialist knowledge and is a wonderful gateway project to build confidence with 3D printers.
One of the big challenges when introducing a new technology into a school is getting busy teachers to take the first step. 3D printing is a very new technology. Teachers from many subject areas are interested but are put off by the time commitment associated with having to learn 3D modelling in addition to learning to drive the printer. This project was successfully created to introduce teachers with no experience of 3D design or 3D printing to using 3D printers.
Recently this project was run at Wellington High School, New Zealand with two groups of Y10 (~15Y.O) students over two weeks by teachers with no 3D modelling experience and only a minimal introduction to using the printers. By the end of the project the teachers (and students) were much more confident about using the 3D printers. They could now see a reason to learn some 3D modelling and were starting to look for other projects that they could be used for.

Objectives The main value of this project is that the 3D printer and 3D design skills are not the main focus. The main focus is on the creation of an original cookie cutter. Teachers: Gain confidence in the 3D printer with simple prints.
Students: Varies depending on the grade level.
  • Younger: Making the cookie cutter: Drawing, cutting, visualising a simplified image.
  • Older: Product design cycle, Modify and simplify a design to work as a cookie cutter, basics of using a 3D printer
    • Audiences This project can be modified to work with any age group. I have run this with students aged from year 0 to 12 (5 to 16Y.0.) Preparation This project intentionally requires very little prior knowledge.
    Suggested resources:
  • Coloured paper, scissors, pens, scanner or digital camera
    OR
  • Computer with 2D drawing program and some experience using it.
    AND
  • Computer with internet access to use cookie caster.
    • The instructor should have gone through this process at least once so they are able to assist students. It is best if the students can take the project through to baking and decorating the cookies. So you will also need
  • Cookie ingredients
  • Cookie decorations
  • Access to an oven
    • Steps!
  • Research your cookie cutter. This could be a character from a book that the class just read. It could be a 3D cookie. For a senior project it could involve market research into appropriate shapes for a new product.
  • Design your cutter. For younger students they can draw and colour in the shape they want to be the cookie. It works best if the design is cut out of coloured paper/card.
  • Take a high contrast photo/scan of the design. Dark card on a light background will not require any extra processing to work with cookie caster. Make sure the cutter takes up the whole frame.
  • Open http://www.cookiecaster.com/ . Use the Trace tool, upload the image. Trace the image with the pen or use the Magic trace tool. Set the size, height and thickness. Smaller cutters mean faster prints so you can get through a whole class with two or three print beds. I find that “Extra Thin” 1mm works well for the wall thickness.
  • Print the cutters. These cutters print very reliably and are unlikely to have any issues. It is a good chance to learn about the difference between printing with a raft and without.
  • Bake, decorate and enjoy!
    • Results At the end of this project students will have a custom cookie cutter to take home. Hopefully they will also have some yummy cookies.
    Grading could be based on the design of the cutter, the outcome of the baking or a description of the design process. Junior example - 5Y.O. This drawing took some post processing before the automatic trace tool in cookie caster would work Classroom example: 14Y.O. Design project example: 16Y.O.

description.text:
It is difficult to pour from a full gallon can without spilling some.
Here's a remix. The spout swivels.
However, it's a somewhat of a work in progress. There may be a better way to turn the spout.
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1223758 Spout for Gallon Cans It can be difficult to pour without spilling from a full gallon can. I bought a new gallon can of WD-40 and of course it's full to the brim, and in trying to fillmy spray bottle's tiny hole (with a funnel) I still spilled quite a bit as the liquid glug-glugs out. So, I searched thingiverse but could not find this spout. Here's my version. If someone already posted this spout then credit to them. It fits the one gallon cans of acetone, paint thinner (mineral spirits), alcohol,laquer thinner, WD-40 etc., found in paint departments in the big box hardware stores. At least it fits all of my cans. I think they use the same cap-thread on all the metal, rectangular gallon cans (in the USA) but who knows.

The critical surface is where the can's lip meets the spout. That should be flat and liquid tight.
But Afinia software insists on putting extra layers of "surface support" under such horizontal surfaces. Sometimes it's not easy to get in there and pry that support off the bottom of a cavity, and it often leaves a rough surface. Printing this spout upside down eliminates that, but requires an extra 4 grams of exterior support material. afinia defau;ts
Right side up: 38 min, 14.5 g material. (5g support)
Upside down: 49 min, 18.5 g material. (9g support) Definately print in nylon or some other chemically resistant material if you plan on using this spout on anything like acetone or laquer thinner.

This is a case I made for SteedMaker's excellent chess set  "thing:34017" , Plus some draughs / checkers pieces.

-Q1,2,3,4 are the four quaters that make up the holder for the pieces.
They are 200mm by 200mm each, to make a case that is 400mm sqaure. your printer must print square and accurately, as there is no room for error
-draughs1 is a single piece, print 12 in each colour
-Chess square is a single piece, 50mm square, print 32 of each colour
I use Repetier Host / Slic3r with marlin firmware, 0.38mm nozzle
My print settings were;
layer height - 0.25
perimeters - 2
top solid layers - 3 4 layers would give a better finish but use more plastic, and take a lot longer to print.
bottom solid layers - 0
fill density - 0.05
Caution when printing the 4 quaters. I found that to get it to print with such low infill, there was quite a bit of printing over mid air which was a bit messy and sometimes curled up, which the NOZZLE WILL RUN INTO, my nozzle is attached very securly and can handle this. The next layer seemed to smooth it out. I take no responsibility for broken hot ends.** The chess peices are a slightly loose fit into the case, if they printed well. The case itself is made from wood, stained and varnished.
3mm glass for the playing surface - window glass from a broken window cut to size.
The sketchup file will show you an exploded view of how it was put together and the dimensions.
Except for the internal dimensions, the rest of the mesurements are not critical, you can alter them to suit yourself.
I used 6mm MDF for the upper and lower base,
a couple of hinges I had lying around
I glued the chess squares to the mdf using ados F2 contact adhesive, starting 5mm from the edge as the MDF 410mm and the playing board is 400mm.
I glued green fabric (pool table baise) to the underside of the board and wrapped it around the edge slightly.
This assembly is held into the frame with the 4 corner fillets which are glued in with wood glue.
I also added some feet.
Make sure everything is perfectly square when gluing together or the plastic inserts (Q1,2,3,4) will not fit !

If you like my work I hope you'll consider supporting me on Pateron: https://www.patreon.com/3DPrintingProfessor Subscribe to me on YouTube: https://www.youtube.com/user/mrjoesays Version 2.1b has been confirm as functional! Thanks nycdesigner and tbuser for sticking with me! This is a complete rebuild of the recorder instruments with more scientific measurements and a more sound theory as well as an entirely unique and slick design. The recorder is one of the oldest woodwind instruments. In the hands of an experienced player it creates a sound synonymous with Renaissance music. Often used in elementary music classes because of it's ease of operation. With 3D printing everyone can have one of their own to make beautiful music on... or wailing screeches if they never got past "hot crossed buns". Ever since I've seen the whistle ( http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1046 ) and it's variations ( http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1046/variations ) I've wondered about the feasibility of extending it to a flute. However when I finally did decide to tackle it I ended up designing the whole thing from scratch (which is why this isn't a derivative of the whistle). Version History:
Ver2.0 - recorderv2mouthpiece.stl + recorderv2body.stl + recorderv2foot.stl: The mouthpiece in this version is the tallest piece at about 119.3mm which is cutting it too close for a TOM. Ver2.1a - recorderv2.1amouthpiece.stl + recorderv2.1body.stl + recorderv2foot.stl: Per input from nycdesigner and tbuser the ring around the base of the parts has been widened to increase stability during print, the mouthpiece has been altered with a shorter windway and 1mm taller window. This brings the mouthpiece to being short enough for a TOM and does not effect tuning tho it may require slightly more air to work. Ver2.1b - recorderv2.1amouthpiece.stl + recorderv2.1body.stl + recorderv2foot.stl: Same as 2.1a except the windway now slopes towards the lip. tbuser found that worked best for his 6 hole flute ( http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:11945 ) so I've included it for experimentation.

Print the 3 parts. Put them together. Warm up the mouthpiece with your hand before playing for best sound. Blow gently. Note that if you start with all holes covered and remove them one-by-one that the high notes are going to sound flat. That is normal. To get the proper tones for all the notes use the key chart on http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Recorder#Recorder_fingering .
